    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Wait, what? I'm not sure I follow the goblin comparison. Can you just stick to the technical side? Specifically, what happens to the pressure readings if the tube gets a blockage in it, like from an insect or debris?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly, let's leave the goblins out of it this time. When the pitot tube gets blocked, it can't measure the dynamic pressure of the air correctly. This blockage can come from insects, debris, or ice. As a result, the pitot tube will only measure the static pressure, which is the pressure of the air around the aircraft when it's not moving. This can lead to incorrect airspeed readings, which can be dangerous for the pilot. It's like trying to measure the speed of a river with a broken ruler; you won't get an accurate reading, and you could end up in trouble. That's why it's crucial to keep the pitot tube clear and functioning properly.",
